body:
Rust's foreign function interface (FFI) allows extern blocks of foreign functions to be defined. The following snippet demonstrates an ffi definition and invocation (inside `lib.rs`):

```rust
#[link(wasm_import_module = "kobby")]
extern "C" {
    /// Get Invoke Arguments
    pub fn __kobby_invoke_args(method_ptr: u32, args_ptr: u32);
}

pub fn kobby_invoke(method_size: u32, args_size: u32) -> bool {
    unsafe { __kobby_invoke_args(method_size, args_size) };
    true
}
```
I have the above snippet in my Rust/WASM library. The `crate-type` is defined in `Cargo.toml` as:

```rust
[lib]
crate-type = ["rlib", "cdylib"]
```
The following is a simple test that references the FFI above (inside the `tests` folder):

```rust
use kobby_ffi_library::invoke::kobby_invoke;

#[test]
fn it_compiles_sanity() {
    assert!(kobby_invoke(0, 0));
}
```
When I run `cargo test`, it produces an `undefined reference to foreign function: __kobby_invoke_args` error, while `cargo test --target wasm32-unknown-unknown` also produces an obscure OS error: `Syntax error: unexpected end of file.`

I have tried changing the  `crate-type` to `["lib", "staticlib", "cdylib"]`, but I still get same errors.

Other than the possibility of having a wrong `#[test]` (in which case the assertion would fail), I don't know what else I'm doing wrong in this scenario. Your support would be greatly appreciated. Thank you!
